{{Infobox religious biography |background = #FFD068 | color = black |name = Issho Fujita |image = |caption = |birth name = |alias = |dharma name = Isshō |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1954|4|18}} |birth_place = [[Niihama]], [[Japan]] |death_date = |death_place = |nationality = |religion = [[Zen Buddhism]] |school = [[Sōtō]] |lineage = |title = Priest, Director |location = |education = Tokyo University, Doctoral chose |occupation = |teacher = [[Kōhō Watanabe]] |reincarnation of = |predecessor = |successor = |students = |spouse = |partner = |children = |website = http://fujitaissho.info/ }} {{nihongo|'''Isshō Fujita'''|藤田 一照|Fujita Isshō|extra=b. 18 April 1954}} was born in [[Niihama, Ehime]], [[Japan]] and was head teacher at [[Valley Zendo]], a [[Sōtō|Sōtō Zen]] practice center in [[Charlemont, Massachusetts]], USA.<ref>{{cite book|title=The complete guide to Buddhist America|year=1998|publisher=Shambhala Publishing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DdcEAAAAYAAJ&q=issho+fujita&dq=issho+fujita&hl=en&ei=EDVPTdigJ4zAsAOHlfn0Cg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CE4Q6AEwCA|author=Don Morreale|accessdate=6 February 2011|page=158}}</ref> Fujita had done studies in [[child psychology]] at [[Tokyo University]] [[Graduate School]], but abandoned them and became a Zen monk. At the age of twenty-nine, on 8 December, Fujita was ordained a Zen priest, along with [[Ryōdō Yamashita]], by [[Kōhō Watanabe]] at [[Antai-ji|Antai-ji temple]].
In 1987, Fujita assumed the role of abbot at Valley Zendo, where he lived until his return to Japan in 2005.
In 2010, he was elected Director of the [[Soto Zen International Center]].
